*&quot;Write less, do more&quot;* is still the very true slogan of jquery. In that spirit I took the liberty of rewriting your script and I condensed it into essentially two lines. As I was not sure about the meaning of your on/off class assignation in `classList.toggle(&#39;navbar-toggle-show&#39;)` I replaced that bit with a simple jquery-`toggle()` function. This is in no way perfect (e. g.: why is the &quot;on&quot; button displayed initially while the navbar is already on?) but maybe it can show you a way to move forward.

I replaced your `$(&quot;.svg-nav&quot;).on(&#39;click&#39;,...)` with `$(&quot;.svg-nav&quot;).click()` as this limits click events to be captured on the `&quot;.svg-nav&quot;`-divs only. Otherwise the click-target could have been the div itself, the underlying svg or even the element inside (circle or path). Having the click target &quot;limited&quot; now allows us to use the `.sibling()` function to act on the &quot;other&quot; button. And this makes it possible to get away with a single function for both buttons.

I also put the contents of your `classToggle()` function into the click-event function, as both functions are triggered essentially at the same point. By using jquery I don&#39;t have to use all of that `forEach()` stuff as jquery will by default act on all matched elements, so the `.toggle()` method will act on all found `.nav-items`. The argument within the toggle()-function checks, whether the click happened on the &quot;On&quot; button which I identified with the `id=&quot;navon&quot;` in the HTML. If so, the element will be made visible, otherwise it will be hidden.

